04322nam a22005175i 9780889207660DE-B159720240306125748.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20061982xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a97808892076607 a10.51644/97808892076602doi  a(DE-B1597)667725  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxccCA 7aBIO0060002bisacsh1 aHunt, Barry D., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aSailor-Scholar :bAdmiral Sir Herbert Richmond 1871-1946 /cBarry D. Hunt. 1aWaterloo, Ontario : bWilfrid Laurier University Press, c[2006] 4c©1982  a1 online resource (272 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFront Matter -- tContents -- tAbbreviations -- tAcknowledgements -- tIntroduction -- tThe Fisher Era: The Education of a Reformer -- tThe Naval Society and Review -- tAt the Admiralty: The First Years of War (1914-1915) -- tCrisis at Sea: The Young Turks' Revolt (1916-1917) -- tThe Wemyss Regime: Great Expectations Unfulfilled (1918-1919) -- tPostwar Readjustments: The View from Greenwich (1920-1923) -- tThe East Indies Station: Singapore, India, and Imperial Defence (1923-1925) -- tThe Imperial Defence College (1926-1928) -- tMadden, "Royal Oak," and "Belligerent Rights": "The Day of the Politician" (1927-1929) -- t"Smaller Navies": The London Naval Conference and Richmond's Retirement (1929-1931) -- tCambridge: The Final Years -- tRetrospective -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aAdmiral Sir Herbert Richmond was "a unique phenomenon in the Victorian-Edwardian navy—a professionally competent and successful officer who was also an intellectual," writes the author. "This was enough to ensure that his progress would be stormy.'' This thoroughly documented biographical study of Richmond's professional career reveals a fully experienced, clear-thinking officer with a profound understanding of naval history, "a restless and uncompromising personality," and a passionate concern with naval strategy, the art of war, and the most effective training programme for officers. Richmond persistently challenged the accepted practices and prejudices of the naval profession. He and his small group of disciples, the "Young Turks," found themselves in the thick of the most crucial controversies in the British Navy. In spite of frequent official displeasure, however, Richmond became an influential naval historian and educator, responsible for the creation of the modern naval staff and the Imperial Defence College. The volume rests on extensive research in the official records and the private papers of Richmond and his close associates. It will interest not only naval historians, but also those with a general interest in the impact of one man's thought and actions on Britain's defence policy and the outcome of two World Wars.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aAdmiralsxBiographyxGreat BritainxGreat Britain. 0aAdmiralszGreat BritainvBiography. 4aBiography & Autobiography. 4aHistory. 7aBIOGRAPHY & AUTOBIOGRAPHY / Historical.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package Pre-2010z978311127416408iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package pre 2010z978311127724040uhttps://doi.org/10.51644/978088920766040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780889207660423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780889207660/original  a978-3-11-127416-4  ACUP Complete eBook-Package Pre-2010b2010  a978-3-11-127724-0  ACUP Upgrade eBook-Package pre 2010b2010  aGBV-deGruyter-alles